======================================================================
SIGNED REDEI THEOREM & F(T, roots of unity)
kind-pasteur-2026-03-14-S70
======================================================================

======================================================================
PART 1: PROOF THAT F(T, -1) IS ALWAYS ODD
======================================================================

  THEOREM: F(T, -1) is odd for any tournament T on n >= 1 vertices.

  PROOF:
  Let e = #{paths with even fwd}, o = #{paths with odd fwd}.
  Then F(1) = e + o = H(T) and F(-1) = e - o.
  By Redei's theorem, H(T) = e + o is ODD.
  Therefore F(-1) = (e + o) - 2o = H - 2o is odd - even = ODD. QED.

  Note: this works because the parity of F(-1) equals the parity of H,
  which is always odd. The SIGNED Redei theorem is a TRIVIAL consequence
  of the UNSIGNED Redei theorem. No new proof needed!

  Verification at n=3: ALL ODD (8 checked)
  Verification at n=4: ALL ODD (64 checked)
  Verification at n=5: ALL ODD (1024 checked)
  Verification at n=6: ALL ODD (5001 checked)

======================================================================
PART 2: F(-1) MOD 4 STRUCTURE
  F(-1) = H - 2o where o = #odd-fwd paths
  F(-1) mod 4 = H mod 4 - 2(o mod 2)
  Since H mod 4 = 1 + 2*alpha_1 mod 4:
  F(-1) mod 4 depends on alpha_1 parity AND o parity
======================================================================

--- n = 4 ---
  F(-1) mod 4 distribution: {1: 32, 3: 32}
  F(-1) mod 4 by H:
    H=  1: {1: 12, 3: 12}
    H=  3: {1: 8, 3: 8}
    H=  5: {1: 12, 3: 12}

